# Default Tor configuration for Resilum.
#
# Tor here serves two roles at once: SOCKS proxy for outbound
# connections (so Reticulum can dial peers' .onion addresses through
# `socks_proxy_*` on TCPClientInterface), and a hidden service that
# publishes our local RNS TCP listener at a globally-reachable
# .onion name.
#
# State and the hidden-service keypair live under /config/tor/ so they
# survive container rebuilds and stay owned by the operator.

DataDirectory /config/tor/data
RunAsDaemon 0

# SOCKS5 proxy for outbound traffic dialing other .onion peers.
SocksPort 127.0.0.1:9050

# Hidden service exposing the local RNS TCP listener (default port
# 4242 from reticulum.config) to the Tor network. The hostname file
# at /config/tor/hidden_service/hostname is read by the discovery
# plugin and broadcast to peers.
HiddenServiceDir /config/tor/hidden_service
HiddenServicePort 4242 127.0.0.1:4242

# ── Pluggable transports / bridges (uncomment in censored regions) ──
#
# In countries that block direct Tor relays (RU, CN, IR, …), Tor needs
# to connect through obfuscated bridges instead of the public relay
# pool. Get fresh ones from https://bridges.torproject.org/ (Telegram
# bot @GetBridgesBot also works), then paste them below and restart
# the container.
#
# UseBridges 1
# ClientTransportPlugin obfs4 exec /usr/bin/obfs4proxy
#
# Add one Bridge line per bridge you got. The lines below are
# placeholders — they will not work as-is.
#
# Bridge obfs4 X.X.X.X:443 FINGERPRINT cert=BASE64 iat-mode=0
# Bridge obfs4 Y.Y.Y.Y:443 FINGERPRINT cert=BASE64 iat-mode=0
#
# Quiet logs by default.
Log notice stdout
